<TEXT>
the shortage of donor organs is so acute 
that hospitals must begin approaching the families of dead patients 
to save other lives a transplant specialist said tuesday 
hospital officials rarely ask grieving families to consider 
donating their loved ones organs said dr calvin stiller head of 
transplant surgery at the university of western ontario 
when they do the question is often so awkwardly worded the 
families immediately reject the idea he said 
sometimes it can be you dont want to donate the organs do 
you said stiller who estimated that at least 80 percent of 
possible donor organs go unused 
a panel of medical experts discussed the problem here tuesday 
during the international congress of transplantation society 
dr oscar salvatierra chief of university of californiasan 
franciscos transplant service said media attention helped find 
donors in some cases 
however publicity doesnt always work considering the 
limited donor pool he told the gathering of about 2700 people 
representing 47 countries 
last year 3993 people in the united states were registered as 
organ donors 
by contrast 13290 transplants were performed according to the 
united network for organ sharing which contracts with the federal 
government to run a national organ distribution network and 
registry 
there are about 20460 patients waiting for organs the unos 
said 
the public should be educated encouraged and cajoled to 
donate for love said dr anthony monaco professor of surgery at 
harvard university 
the government could pay the donor he said 
say everyone could get a government insurance policy if 
they will agree to donate he said 
but stiller said many in the medical and scientific communities 
opposed paying donors 
donating is no longer a charitable event its an 
obligation he 
