distraught people telephone the gulf support group 
for news of relatives stranded in kuwait and iraq but they often 
end up talking about themselves 
when people call looking for information we ask them are you 
all right and other questions which will elicit how they are 
coping joanna copley one of the hotline organizers said monday 
ms copleys 27yearold sister katharine was on board a 
british airways flight that stopped for fuel in kuwait on aug 2 
the day iraq invaded the emirate as of friday she was still in 
that occupied country 
many of the callers like the widow whose only child is in 
kuwait do not want advice theyre just looking for a soothing 
voice and a friendly ear to hear them work through their grief 
anger frustration and guilt 
they feel guilty first because they are safe in england and 
secondly because if theyve had a family quarrel they may wish 
that theyd left on better terms and that there may never be a 
chance to make things right ms copley said in an interview at 
the hotline offices 
the hotline was set up aug 7 as an information clearing house 
for relatives of britons stranded in kuwait and iraq it receives 
up to 200 calls each day said ms copley 29 a computer 
consultant 
her pearls and countrystyle dress with a large white ribbon 
belie a steely determination i dont know why i decided to act 
maybe i react faster or get angry quicker she said 
the foreign office estimates there are 4000 british citizens in 
