<TEXT>
scientists are turning an isolated 
island into a laboratory to test a genetically engineered rabies 
vaccine on raccoons 
in the first field test of the vaccine in the united states 26 
scientists monday took boats to parramore island and put out 4000 
doses of the vaccine inside baited tubes to attract the 400 
raccoons on the strip of land 
over the next year some of the animals will be caught alive and 
tested to see if the vaccine produced antibodies to fight rabies 
raccoons are the biggest source of rabies in the united states 
often transmitting the virus to dogs and cats that tangle with them 
if we can control rabies in the raccoon population we will 
have come a long way in handling rabies in pets said dr suzanne 
jenkins assistant epidemiologist with the state health department 
the only sign of man on the 10milelong barrier island is a 
coast guard station at one end 
we knew we needed an island for this test because we wanted 
limited access and a population of raccoons that would not be 
wandering off somewhere ms jenkins said since this is a 
test it was felt it would be better if there was not public 
access you dont let people into your laboratory what weve done 
is create an outdoor laboratory 
the vaccine developed by philadelphias wistar institute is 
inserted into small tubes of soft plastic treated with fish oil 
then the bait is covered with a crab slurry crab parts that 
have been left out for awhile to attract the raccoons said 
warren b cheston wistar associate director as a raccoon chews on 
the bait the liquid vaccine is released in its mouth 
the wistar is the nations oldest nonprofit biomedical research 
institute 
using genetic engineering wistar took from the rabies virus a 
minute piece of genetic material that induces formation of 
antibodies and grafted that fragment onto the harmless vaccinia 
virus used in smallpox vaccine 
a similar vaccine is being used in europe and canada to control 
rabies in foxes scientists believe the wistar vaccine could have 
broader application 
robert miller of the us department of agriculture said if the 
test on parramore island works the department will approve a 
mainland test of the vaccine cheston said wistar has been working 
with pennsylvania to find a test site 
the vaccine engineered in 1982 may be available within five 
years 
ms jenkins said the bait could be spread from airplanes as is 
being done in canada 
i could see using it to produce corridors of vaccinated 
animals around population centers to keep rabies out she said 
you could encircle isolated cases of rabies in the same manner 
and keep it from spreading 
</TEXT>
