<TEXT>
by midday monday the temperature in the 
saudi desert was probably 130 degrees but lt col jim mattis 
wouldnt know his thermometer only reaches 120 
the desert is a cruel place as the marine platoon in the hills 
several miles from the nearest road is finding out by 830 am 
monday the sun was so hot a group of marines in a mortar unit 
gladly remained hidden under their camouflaged tents 
we just try to rest when we can and stay cool when we can 
said one in line with defense department rules neither he nor any 
of the enlisted men could give their names and the location of 
their unit could not be disclosed 
the marines tents covered with camouflaged netting were so 
well concealed that only their vague outline could be distinguished 
in the brown sand 
a group of marines relaxed on tarps under one big tent while 
smaller numbers manned the mortars and served as lookouts 
the marines have trained in the mojave desert but the united 
states has not been involved in a desert campaign since the united 
states and great britain joined together to defeat the germans in 
north africa in 1943 
because of the heat the men usually keep watch just two hours 
at a time in their off hours they sleep eat bone up on desert 
warfare tactics and perform chores such as cleaning their guns 
all marines are issued three packages of food mres for meal 
ready to eat daily each package contains about 3000 calories in 
the form of crackers a beef or chicken meal cheese cookies and 
dehydrated fruit 
water is one of the biggest challenges in the desert marines 
are told to drink five gallons a day which is brought in by 
water buffalo or military trailers used to haul water 
to ward off the sun they cover their skin use sunscreen and 
wear hats and sunglasses 
even so they are only kept out in the desert for three days 
before rotating back to the makeshift barracks usually big 
airconditioned rooms 
while the heat is overpowering several marines said their 
biggest fear is the threat of chemical weapons 
each marine has a gas mask plus three vials of atropen an 
antidote to nerve gas should a marine be exposed to the gas he 
must inject himself with the agent 
for the marines one of the biggest frustrations is being out of 
touch with world events 
even maj gen john hopkins head of the 7th marine 
expeditionary brigade said he had no time to listen to the radio 
to find out what the reaction in the united states was to the 
deployment 
