<TEXT>
texans soon will be able to see previously secret 
documents stemming from legal battles including those fought over 
sensitive environmental and productliability cases 
civil liberties advocates goodgovernment groups and media 
organizations are hailing the state supreme courts 
firstinthenation procedural change which takes effect sept 1 
its not that we expect on the first day a line of people 
walking into the courthouse said jim harrington texas civil 
liberties union legal director but the rules will turn the files 
there into a public library for our watchdogs 
environmentalists and consumer organizations were particularly 
thrilled by the change adopted in april at the request of the 
legislature they frequently have won settlements only to have 
sealed court records keep information on toxic substances and other 
hazards unavailable 
if a manufacturer loses a lawsuit such as exploding gas tanks 
on an automobile that information cant be sealed up and filed 
away in a file drawer someplace said tom smith director of 
public citizen a consumer rights group in austin 
maintaining open records can do nothing but help protect the 
public said mary kelly an austin lawyer and legal coordinator 
for the sierra club in texas 
but dane harris president of the texas association of business 
said the rule could hurt businesses that may become targets of 
lawsuitminded attorneys on fishing expeditions 
we feel like it opens up the opportunity for people to become 
aware of sometimes competitive tradesensitive information we 
think it invites needless litigation said harris whose 
organization urged the justices not to adopt the rule 
we feel like just having these records available for whoever 
wants to go on a fishing expedition is not conducive to a 
probusiness climate that will maintain and create jobs 
some defense lawyers also have claimed the threat of publicizing 
court documents would hurt their chances of obtaining settlements 
the rules adopted by a 54 vote say no court order or opinion 
may be sealed other records are presumed open and can be sealed 
only by showing a serious or substantial interest 
the new rules open discovery documents those exchanged by 
opposing lawyers before trial if they contain information that 
could affect public safety or governmental operations 
it is extremely important in that some of the best information 
on hazardous chemicals has been developed through litigation 
said ms kelly in litigation everyone is motivated to find out 
as much as they can through discovery a lot of information on the 
hazards of asbestos was blown open through litigation 
the rules do not cover divorce records and other family matters 
some monetary amounts in settlements and pretrial matters involving 
trade secrets 
madelyn applebaum spokeswoman for the association of trial 
lawyers of america said texas was the first to adopt the rules 
although florida has since adopted such a policy and efforts are 
under way in new york to release records 
she said two weeks ago the rhode island governor vetoed a bill 
that would have adopted similar rules 
