<TEXT>
yemen on tuesday agreed it would turn away 
an iraqi oil tanker expected to arrive within hours the agreement 
followed an emergency security council meeting called on the matter 
us ambassador thomas pickering said the united states 
requested the emergency council meeting after it received 
information of the imminent arrival in yemen of the tanker which 
defied a us warship that fired across its bow saturday 
in the course of the evening the yemeni permanent 
representative told the council that yemen would adhere to the 
sanctions on iraqi goods imposed after iraqs aug 2 invasion of 
kuwait pickering said 
yemen the 15member councils only arab member had abstained 
from the sanctions vote but had joined with the council in 
declaring the iraqi annexation of kuwait null and void yemen 
had also abstained from an arab league vote on sanctions 
diplomats said the tanker would arrive in yemeni territorial 
waters within hours 
pickering said the council also accepted a us draft resolution 
that asked the united nations to define what force it would take to 
back up its embargo 
the british ambassador sir crispin tickell also said the 
yemeni representative agreed to turn away the tanker 
the council agreed to convene at an early date to consider 
the resolution pickering said the adjournment was to allow each of 
the 15 security council members to consult with their governments 
before the final vote 
a formal meeting was possible today or wednesday to adopt a 
resolution calling for international military action against iraq 
diplomats said 
the draft proposal that called for members to take all 
necessary action to enforce the un embargo against iraq it 
would authorize the deployment of maritime forces and the use of 
minimum force as may be necessary to verify the cargoes and 
destinations of all shipping and to ensure the strict 
enforcement of the embargo 
the cuban delegation also presented a separate proposal calling 
for the exclusion of foodstuffs medicine and medical assistance 
from the un embargo 
the united states has been criticized by some countries for 
policing the un embargo without council approval 
france and the soviet union are believed to be supportive while 
china is said to be wary but unlikely to block an enforcement 
resolution with a veto 
there is no exact precedent for the loose international military 
action currently contemplated diplomats close to the negotiations 
described the talks as complicated and requiring legal research 
the diplomats emphasized that the united states and britain were 
not seeking to invoke article 42 of the un charter providing for 
a unsponsored blockade to enforce sanctions 
that article has never been invoked the last un enforcement 
action was launched in korea in 1950 that operation however was 
placed under a us command and was not organized under article 42 
neither the united states nor britain they said wanted a un 
commander to organize their national military actions even a un 
flag could imply some unacceptable un supervision they said 
the only precedent for un enforcement of sanctions came in 
1966 when the security council called upon britain to prevent by 
force if necessary oil shipments to whiteruled rhodesia which 
later was the object of a broad embargo 
on aug 6 the security council adopted sweeping economic 
sanctions against iraq to punish the baghdad government for 
invading and occupying kuwait on aug 2 
the security council last met saturday night to condemn iraqs 
holding foreigners against their will it demanded their immediate 
release 
under chapter 7 article 42 of the un charter the security 
council is empowered to take military action to enforce its 
sanctions the charter provies that the council may take such 
action by air sea or land forces as may be necessary to maintain 
or restore international peace and security 
such action it says may include a blockade 
</TEXT>
