<TEXT>
a wisconsin appeals court has cleared the 
way for the start this fall of a program that pays poor milwaukee 
children state money to attend private school 
several groups including the states biggest teachers union 
had sought an injunction blocking the program while they appeal a 
dane county circuit court decision earlier this month that ruled it 
constitutional 
but the court of appeals on monday refused saying there was no 
evidence any irreparable harm would occur if the program went into 
effect 
the program the first of its kind in the united states offers 
2500 in tuition assistance for up to 1000 poor pupils to enroll 
in private school it is scheduled to start when fall classes begin 
in about two weeks 
supporters and opponents of the program have 19 days from monday 
to file briefs in the appeals case 
at the hearing charles clausen representing the wisconsin 
education association council and the other groups said the 
program was unconstitutional because the legislature failed to pass 
it as a separate bill it was an item in the budget bill 
but attorneys for the state six private schools and families 
who support the program defended the legislature arguing it acted 
decisively to improve the quality of education in urban areas 
about 400 pupils have been accepted by 10 private milwaukeearea 
schools participating in the program which won legislative 
approval in april 
