the us proposal called for members to take all necessary 
action to enforce the un embargo against iraq 
it would authorize the deployment of maritime forces and the use 
of minimum force as may be necessary to verify the cargoes and 
destinations of all shipping and to ensure the strict 
enforcement of the embargo 
the cuban delegation presented a separate proposal calling for 
the exclusion of foodstuffs medicine and medical assistance from 
the un embargo 
the united states has been criticized by some countries for 
policing the un embargo without council approval 
france and the soviet union are believed supportive while china 
is said to be wary but unlikely to block an enforcement resolution 
there is no exact precedent for the loose international military 
action currently contemplated 
diplomats said the united states and britain were not seeking to 
invoke article 42 of the un charter providing for a 
unsponsored blockade to enforce sanctions 
that article has never been invoked the last un enforcement 
action was launched in korea in 1950 that operation however was 
placed under a us command and was not organized under article 42 
the only precedent for un enforcement of sanctions came in 
1966 when the security council called upon britain to prevent by 
force if necessary oil shipments to whiteruled rhodesia later 
the object of a broad embargo 
on aug 6 the security council adopted sweeping economic 
sanctions against iraq to punish the baghdad government for its 
aug 2 invasion of kuwait and subsequent annexation of that nation 
the security council last met saturday to condemn iraqs holding 
foreigners against their will it demanded their immediate release 
under chapter 7 article 42 of the un charter the security 
council is empowered to take military action to enforce its 
sanctions the charter provies that the council may take such 
action by air sea or land forces as may be necessary to maintain 
or restore international peace and security 
such action it says may include a blockade 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

<DOC>
