if kalugin is elected to represent krasnodar province in the 
congress of peoples deputies he will gain parliamentary immunity 
allowing him to continue to criticize the kgb without fear of 
prosecution 
after kalugin publicly accused the secret police in june of 
resisting reform and continuing to carry out dirty tricks he was 
dismissed and stripped of his rank becoming an unlikely hero to 
soviet radicals 
the soviet prosecutor has been investigating him under a law 
that prohibits divulging state secrets but no formal charges have 
been filed 
the 55yearold former major general who was a kgb agent in the 
united states throughout the 1960s has hurt the kgbs recent 
effort to improve its image the secret police long associated 
with purges and repression reorganized itself this year 
officially eliminating the directorate responsible for harassment 
of dissidents it has undertaken a public relations campaign aimed 
at inspiring trust instead of fear 
kalugin has insisted that the kgb still infiltrates trade unions 
and the russian orthodox church taps the telephones of many 
citizens and engages in dirty tricks abroad 
tass said about 60 percent of the voters turned out for sundays 
election in krasnodar a heavily agricultural region along the 
black sea about 750 miles south of moscow the runoff election 
scheduled sept 2 is necessary because none of the 21 candidates 
won a clear majority of the votes 
interfax an independent soviet news service said kalugin 
received 959082 votes just under 45 percent of the total number 
cast gorovoi the next highest votegetter received 227572 
votes or nearly 11 percent he is deputy chairman of the regional 
agroindustrial committee and previously served as chairman of a 
collective farm 
among the other candidates were anatoly berezovoi a pilot and 
cosmonaut who took a 211day space flight in 1982 and gen 
vladimir sein political chief of the transcaucasian military 
district their vote totals were unavailable 
the kgb and its supporters attempted to discredit kalugin before 
the election and one resident said in a letter to the newspaper 
arguments and facts that it was rumored people who voted for 
kalugin would be imprisoned 
pravda the communist party newspaper said tuesday the election 
campaign was unusually sharp and tense sometimes going beyond 
the bounds of decency 
kalugin served as a kgb operative in the united states from 1958 
to 1970 first under the cover of a radio moscow correspondent and 
later as a first secretary in the soviet embassy in washington 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

