<TEXT>
a government air traffic controller who lost 
his dulles airport job after he began taking an antiaids drug has 
accepted a lowerlevel faa position in miami the controller said 
tuesday 
ron wilkinson said he would continue to pursue an 
antidiscrimination complaint against the federal aviation 
administration and planned to file a federal court suit alleging 
discrimination based on a handicap 
faa spokesman roger meyers in miami confirmed that wilkinson 
29 had been offered a job in the faas miami control center but 
said he didnt know whether the job had been accepted 
the faa suspended wilkinsons medical certificate in july 1989 
when he told his superiors at dulles which serves the washington 
metropolitan area that he was taking the drug azt or zidovudine 
after testing positive for the presence of hiv virus 
the faa says that controllers who have the critical duty of 
monitoring and directing aircraft are to be given less critical 
jobs if they take azt wilkinson said he was only offered another 
job at dulles months later after being put on forced leave 
he had argued that the faa should offer him a job in miami where 
he was being treated by a doctor and had a group of people helping 
him deal with his exposure to aids wilkinson said he has none of 
the symptoms of aids itself and has been healthy since his medical 
certificate was lifted 
a person who tests positive for antibodies to the aids virus has 
a 20 percent to 30 percent chance of developing aids over a 
fiveyear period according to the federal centers for disease 
control 
acquired immune deficiency syndrome attacks the bodys immune 
system rendering it incapable of resisting other diseases and 
infections 
the faa has said azt may impair a controllers ability to keep 
track of aircraft 
wilkinson his lawyers and the controllers union have disputed 
that saying medical evidence shows no serious side effects from 
use of the drug 
wilkinson said he has accepted a job as an air traffic 
assistant with a salary 4000 lower than his earnings as a full 
controller in accepting he said he retained his right to pursue 
the antidiscrimination case the new job also will deny him an 
additional 4000 in overtime and differential pay he said 
the faa has yet to confirm his employment or set a starting date 
for the new job he said 
the agency gave him until aug 22 to accept or reject the offer 
he said 
wilkinson said he has nearly 11 years of federal service 
including eight years as an air force controller he said he would 
have qualified as a toplevel controller in about a year if his 
certificate had not been voided 
