drug control cooperation between the united 
states and mexico is expected to improve in the coming year but the 
next few months will be critical in dealing with new governments of 
colombia and peru the state department said tuesday 
in a midyear update of its annual international narcotics 
control strategy report the departments bureau of international 
narcotics matters said it is encouraged by developments in the 
fight against cocaine but the heroin situation gives less reason 
for optimism 
with new governments of two of the andean nations colombia 
and peru the coming months will be critical if the hemispheric 
commitment to narcotics is to be sustained and tangible progress 
made in dismantling trafficking networks and reducing the cocaine 
supply the department said 
it said the outgoing government of peru declined to sign an 
agreement for 35 million in us military aid to assist in 
counternarcotics efforts but new president alberto fujimori has 
indicated a commitment to continuing the counternarcotics effort 
as well as a willingness to conclude agreements on military 
assistance 
it said the colombian government has continued to extradite 
major drug traffickers and money launderers to the united states 
an action which colombian traffickers fear most 
given recent decreases in reported cocaine usage in the united 
states and reported reductions in emergency room incidents 
involving cocaine these developments in the andes provide reasons 
for encouragement the report said 
the us and mexico continued to cooperate closely on cocaine 
interdiction and we expect that cooperation between the us 
and mexico will continue to improve during the coming year the 
department said 
however the department said the international heroin 
situation is not as encouraging as that of cocaine overproduction 
of opium has kept prices down in the us and europe and the supply 
of heroin is abundant worldwide 
