<TEXT>
more than two dozen groups filed a lawsuit 
tuesday challenging a nuclear regulatory commission decision to 
ease controls on the disposal of lowlevel nuclear wastes 
the lawsuit filed in the us court of appeals here said the 
new policy means unhealthy levels of radiation could be left in the 
soil and buildings at closed nuclear power plants and that 
radioactive contamination could drift into the ground water at 
garbage dumps 
the lawsuit also alleges that nrc didnt provide for adequate 
public participation before issuing the new policy in june 
the nrcs rule trades off peoples lives in favor of the 
financial interests of the nuclear industry said joan claybrook 
president of public citizen one of the environmental groups that 
filed the lawsuit 
the nrc said it would on a casebycase basis deregulate the 
disposal of certain lowlevel atomic wastes from nuclear power 
plants hospitals laboratories and other facilities if the 
radioactive emissions are considered below regulatory concern 
under the new policy such wastes could be disposed of in 
conventional landfills all radioactive wastes under previous nrc 
policy automatically must be given special precautions and taken to 
designated disposal sites 
the nrc has argued that many of the lowlevel wastes now 
requiring special treatment emit such a low dosage of radiation 
that they dont pose a health concern 
in addition to public citizen other groups joining the lawsuit 
were the us public interest research group the natural resources 
defense council the nuclear information and resource service and 
physicians for social responsibility 
