subcommittee of the house public works and transportation 
committee said there is opposition to random alcohol testing on 
civil liberties grounds 
besides oberstar said aviation experts consider the heavy 
drinking by the three former northwest airlines pilots an 
aberration 
were not talking about an epidemic thats for sure 
oberstar said 
according to the ntsb there have been only 16 airline accidents 
since 1983 in which drug or alcohol use by pilots was found to be a 
factor none of involved a crash of a major airline 
the faa office in oklahoma city said it has recorded 126 pilot 
revocations and 111 suspensions for drug and alcohol violations in 
the past five years only 36 of the pilots worked for commercial 
passengercarrying airlines and 12 of those had their licenses 
revoked including prouse kirchner and balzer the faa said 
joann sloane an faa spokeswoman in washington said the trial 
has heightened awareness of the problem but hasnt prompted changes 
in faa policy 
major us airlines arent planning changes in their alcohol 
policies said kathleen henriques spokeswoman for the air 
transport association 
they are continually talking about drinking and flying she 
said there hasnt been anything spurred by this incident 
