<TEXT>
a government report showing a sharp rise in 
the number of food stamp recipients reveals a lot more poor people 
in the united states than many wish to admit the chairman of a 
congressional committee on hunger said tuesday 
it shows you to a certain extent the sleeping giant that is 
out there said rep tony hall dohio in a statement released 
by his office following published reports about an agriculture 
department study on food stamps 
he said the findings in the report demonstrate how even a slight 
downturn in the economy can be too much for some people throwing 
them onto public assistance rolls 
the report a summary of which was furnished by the agriculture 
department on tuesday said the number of people using food stamps 
rose by more than 1 million between the second quarter of fiscal 
1989 and the second quarter of this fiscal year pushing the 
overall figure to just over 20 million 
the rise extended to 44 states and the district of columbia 
varying in size and timing from state to state nearly half the 
total increase was attributable to a rise in recipients in texas 
california and florida the report said 
agriculture department investigators found no consensus about 
the causes of the increases they said the increases are so recent 
that much of the data traditionally used to analyze food stamp 
trends are not available 
however the study offers several possible reasons for the 
increases including greater unemployment more working poor 
higher food prices changes in the distribution of income more 
female heads of household changes in the immigration laws giving 
thousands of aliens legal status and making them eligible for food 
stamps and improved accessibility and outreach 
food stamps are an entitlement said halls statement it 
doesnt make any sense to create an entitlement program and then 
keep it a secret at some time everyone is going to have to come to 
grips with the fact that we have this many poor people 
further studies will be done to improve the food stamp program 
said a committee staff member also hearings on poverty in america 
will be held soon by the house select committee on hunger which 
hall chairs 
the house earlier this month approved a farm bill that would 
expand access to the food assistance program the house approved 
181 billion for fiscal 1991 the senate has yet to act 
the agriculture department study was undertaken at the request 
of the senate appropriations committee which was concerned about 
the recent rise in recipients 
the bush administration anticipating 181 million food stamp 
recipients this year requested 133 billion for fiscal 1990 
congress approved 148 billion and later provided another 12 
billion when the initial amount proved to be too low 
