<TEXT>
leftist rebels stepped up attacks on 
government troops throughout el salvador on tuesday as hopes waned 
for a ceasefire accord in the latest round of talks aimed at 
ending the 10yearold civil war 
guerrillas staged a series of attacks on army positions south 
and east of the capital san salvador authorities said 
the attacks came after rebels used bombs hurled from homemade 
catapaults and mortars to attack an army barracks in san salvador 
across the street from president alfredo cristianis residence 
eleven people were killed and 12 were wounded in the fighting on 
monday and tuesday according to official and civilian sources 
as the fighting intensified government and rebel negotiators 
became less optimistic that any ceasefire accord would result from 
the current round of peace talks being held in san jose the costa 
rican capital 
it could be said that we are stuck and i dont believe we 
will reach substantial accords by the end of this meeting said 
the chief government negotiator salvadoran justice minister oscar 
santamaria before going into tuesdays negotiating session 
a rebel negotiator dagoberto gutierrez said if there is no 
government movement toward our proposal we would say that there 
wont be any spectacular accords 
both sides had expressed optimism an agreement might be reached 
when the current round of talks began friday between 
representatives of cristianis conservative usbacked government 
and the leftist farabundo marti national liberation front the 
talks are scheduled to conclude wednesday 
the talks are the fourth round of negotiations this year aimed 
at reaching agreement on a ceasefire by sept 15 
but un mediator alvaro de soto said it was unlikely there 
would be a ceasefire agreement by then 
given the dynamics of the negotiation process its impossible 
to arrive at a negotiated ceasefire agreement before sept 15 
de soto said 
but that doesnt mean that the negotiations wont continue 
he said 
the negotiators have made little progress toward reaching a 
compromise on rebel demands for reducing the size of the military 
and purging and punishing officers responsible for human rights 
abuses 
government officials have said discussions on the size of the 
army and a purge of officers should come only after a ceasefire 
neither side has agreed to suspend military actions during the 
negotiations 
a guerrilla spokesman said the attack on the barracks near 
cristianis residence was meant to pressure the government into 
softening its position in the talks 
this is how were going to crack the killer governments lack 
of will to negotiate said a guerrilla who read a communique 
monday on the local san salvador radio sonora 
in washington the state department said tuesday that the attack 
on the army barracks raises doubts about the rebels willingness to 
negotiate 
the guerrillas should immediately cease these attacks and 
negotiate seriously to end the war said the departments deputy 
spokesman richard boucher 
one civilian was killed and five others wounded in monday 
nights battle near the barracks military sources said but the 
rebels said no one was killed and only four civilians were wounded 
the rebels expressed regrets that civilians were wounded in the 
attack calling it a serious error in operational procedures 
we have given instructions that measures should be taken so 
that these types of incidents should not happen again the rebels 
said in a news release issued in mexico city 
army troops backed by helicopter gunships exchanged automatic 
rifle fire for about 30 minutes with the rebels before the 
attackers withdrew 
the military sources who spoke on condition of anonymity said 
none of the rebel rounds hit the barracks which houses a military 
communications unit 
an official at cristianis residence said the president was not 
there at the time of the attack and denied radio reports that a 
mortar round hit the building 
on tuesday guerrillas attacked army positions in jucuapan san 
agustin and santa elena in usulutan province in eastern el 
salvador military officials reported 
the heaviest fighting was in jucuapan 68 miles southeast of san 
salvador where six rebels one national guardsman and one 
civilian were killed officials said three guardsmen and one 
civilian were wounded there were no reports of casualties 
elsewhere in the province 
more than 73000 people the majority of them civilians have 
been killed since the civil war began in october 1979 
