<TEXT>
a federal judge tuesday ordered 
mississippi to pay more than 6 million to settle a 1970 lawsuit 
accusing the state employment agency of systematic racial and sex 
discrimination 
the settlement was the first of its kind in the united states 
said richard t seymour of the washington dcbased lawyers 
committee for civil rights under law which represented the 
plaintiffs 
im glad this has come to a closure and hope that employment 
services across the country will take this to heart seymour said 
us district judge lt senter jr ordered the state to pay 
47 million to about 760 former black and female clients of the 
employment services cleveland office the state also must pay 14 
million in attorneys fees 
this was no surprise said fred lotterhos general counsel 
for the state employment security commission he said there had 
been negotiations for the settlement for some time 
we stress the fact this happened a long long time ago what 
the court found we were doing wrong we are not doing that way 
anymore lotterhos said 
the lawsuit originally was filed in 1970 by rosie lee pegues and 
three other blacks the complaint later was amended to cover more 
than 1500 black or female plaintiffs who applied for assistance 
from the agencys cleveland office 
a federal appeals court ruled in 1983 that the cleveland office 
was guilty of referring blacks to lowpaying domestic and service 
jobs while reserving more desirable openings for whites it also 
found that the office discriminated against women by accepting 
orders for maleonly openings 
the court ruling covered blacks who sought jobs through the 
cleveland office in 1970 and women who applied for jobs between 
1969 and 1973 
the settlement amount was determined by comparing the salaries 
the plaintiffs made and the salaries of jobs they might have had if 
they had been referred by the cleveland office lotterhos said 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

