<TEXT>
even as the highest court in the land 
drifts rightward the highest court in new jersey is staking out 
bold stands in the opposite direction and it is gaining influence 
the impact this court has had is incredible said ronald 
kl collins a state court expert and a visiting associate 
professor at catholic university in washington dc 
there is a battle going on between the united states supreme 
court and the new jersey supreme court for the conscience of the 
courts across the country on many issues the question is do we 
go with the united states supreme court or with new jersey 
collins said 
to go with new jersey is take a dizzying tour of judicial 
activism 
in the past three months alone the new jersey court has ruled 
the state must ensure that as much money is spent to educate 
children in poor cities as is spent on those in wealthy suburbs 
that police cannot sift through roadside trash without a search 
warrant and that warning labels on cigarette packages cannot 
shield tobacco companies from liability suits 
these decisions add to a legacy of assertiveness this was the 
court that allowed karen ann quinlans parents to remove their 
comatose daughter from a respirator and condemned surrogate 
motherhood in the baby m case 
the court also has ordered that housing for lowincome residents 
be built in every municipality it has ruled that poor women have 
the right to statefinanced abortions to protect their health 
when the court found that the state wasnt contributing enough 
dollars to provide a fair education to poor students 14 years ago 
it closed public schools the legislature then adopted an income 
tax to come up with the money 
often the seven state justices are on a collision course with 
the us supreme court in these cases new jersey justices rely on 
the states 43yearold constitution saying it provides greater 
protections than afforded by federal court decisions 
richard j hughes a former governor and chief justice who wrote 
the landmark quinlan decision said the new jersey state 
constitution is a font of individual liberties thats why our 
court many times goes a little further than the united states 
supreme court 
constitutional experts say such actions are spurring other state 
supreme courts to become more aggressive 
the new jersey panel is helping set a course where state bills 
of rights are seen as independent sources of bills of rights 
said g alan tarr chairman of the political science department at 
rutgers university and an author of several books on the court 
but critics say the new jersey court goes too far 
the new jersey supreme court makes earl warren seem like a 
timid soul said bruce fein a constitutional scholar and former 
official with the conservative heritage foundation theyve been 
involved in social engineering and theyve been rather inept at 
it 
he rejects the notion that new jersey is leading an offensive by 
state courts only about a dozen courts are becoming more 
active he said leaving 38 reasonably conservative courts that 
stay with the us supreme court 
other courts didnt always turn to new jersey before the 
adoption of the 1947 constitution its courts were political plums 
harvested by party bosses 
we discarded the worst court system in the country for the 
best said hughes 
constitutional experts say a combination of factors have led new 
jersey down a path few courts have traveled although lawmakers and 
governors have criticized the court they have stayed clear of 
exacting political revenge the new jersey justices are appointed 
not elected the governor and state senate can remove or reappoint 
justices seven years after they join the court if they are 
reappointed they serve until age 70 
they have the ability to get involved without too much 
political backlash said tarr there are no elections they can 
make decisions without playing political football 
tarr noted that former gov thomas h kean who branded the 
courts decision on lowincome housing communistic nonetheless 
reappointed two justices who supported it including chief justice 
robert n wilentz 
some of the courts landmark decisions have been a matter of 
coincidence the quinlan and baby m cases just happened to take 
place in new jersey 
but supporters and critics agree the courts reputation is no 
coincidence in new jersey the supreme court has long had no 
qualms about hearing cases other courts wont touch and it has 
consistently said government has an obligation to protect 
individual rights 
the court has said you show us a case with enough injustice 
and we will not refrain from acting collins said 
the courts actions on lowincome housing and school funding 
link constitutional justice to economic justice he said it 
says that justice is not limited to liberty but also to economics 
this is constitutional law at its zenith and its most controversial 
stage 
it has raised the ire of critics who say the court is stretching 
the state constitution their imagination has been triggered by 
something other than the state constitution the court is making 
all of these obligations out of nothing fein said 
as the federal courts become more conservative experts agree 
the new jersey supreme court will continue to command center stage 
the new jersey court has spawned an environment about the kind 
of cases that can be tried there said collins cases that 
wont go before other courts will come to new jersey 
