<TEXT>
employees at survival technology inc are 
accelerating production of an item they hope will never be used a 
nerve gas antidote for american troops in the mideast 
it helps the company but youve got to be concerned because 
it means theres a war going on somewhere and thats not good 
said j frank harmon director of manufacturing for the companys 
pharmaceutical division 
survival technology based in bethesda md makes 95 percent of 
the noncommunist worlds supply of the antidote at its plant here 
in suburban st louis 
it is the only american supplier of the antidote which troops 
in the persian gulf area may need if iraqi president saddam hussein 
uses his stockpile of deadly poisonous gases 
six days after iraq invaded kuwait on aug 2 the defense 
department asked the company to speed up production of 85000 kits 
it wasnt scheduled to deliver until the end of september 
at the same time the government asked for an additional 2 
million worth which harmon said amounted to several hundred 
thousand kits of two autoinject drugfilled syringes 
in response the company delayed its annual summer maintenance 
shutdown and asked 31 production employees to postpone vacations to 
help finish the order over the weekend all said they would 
they take tremendous pride in manufacturing something knowing 
that lives are very literally at stake harmon said 
employees said they didnt mind canceling vacation plans and 
working 10and 12hour days to get the order completed 
you know its a crucial time but were glad to be here to be 
able to help support the government said employee wanda moose 
every syringe i make is just like saving a life 
harmon said the company expected to ship the second order in 
about a month additional orders from friendly foreign governments 
also are expected to come in he said unlike the united states 
some countries do not have any of the antidote in stock 
the federal governments request came as us troops and planes 
moved into saudi arabia for a possible confrontation with iraq 
although chemical warfare was banned by the geneva disarmament 
conference in 1971 because of its heinous nature iraq used nerve 
gas and mustard gas in its eightyear war with iran and against its 
own kurdish minority 
while there is no known antidote to mustard gas which burns the 
skin on contact the antidote survival technology makes is 
effective against all known forms of nerve gas harmon said 
the antidote kit consists of atropine which stops the 
paralyzing effects of nerve gas and pralidoxime chloride which 
helps return the bodys functions to normal 
harmon said soldiers carry three packs of the antidote each of 
which is effective for two to six hours depending on how soon the 
drugs are administered 
to help speed the delivery of the drugs they are contained in 
two separate springloaded injectors about the size of cigars the 
soldier pulls off the cap and presses the injector against his 
thigh the spring inside fires the hidden needle into his leg even 
through heavy protective clothing 
the autoejector device was invented by the companys founder 
the late stanley sarnoff who was a cardiologist at the national 
institutes of health sarnoff was looking for a way for people to 
easily administer lifesaving drugs including nerve gas antidote on 
the battlefield 
before the autoinjector the military used a needle attached to 
a small tube the soldier had to push the needle under his skin and 
squeeze the tube to administer the drug 
most syringes are rather imposing harmon said a lot of 
people have a real aversion to needles 
with the autoinjector as soon as you feel the pinch its 
over he said 
since 1975 the company has made more than 50 million doses of 
the nerve gas antidote and can make 15 million a month at full 
production the kits cost about 10 and have a shelf life of five 
years harmon said 
the plant generally produces several million doses a year it 
also has sold the antidote kits to other countries including 
canada jordan and israel 
</TEXT>
