<TEXT>
when lukasz malachowski edited an influential 
weekly back home in poland the bottom line was maintaining 
journalistic integrity while avoiding the ire of communist 
government censors 
came the revolution and all that changed the censors were gone 
but so were the government subsidies for essentials like paper and 
ink competing for survival became the new bottom line 
everything was subsidized or donated we never had to think 
whether it could be sold or not now we have to think over all 
these things or nobody will be able to survive says malachowski 
35 whose catholic weekly review essentially went broke with the 
change to a market economy 
this summer malachowski is one of 15 eastern european 
journalists spending 10 weeks at american magazine like elle 
rolling stone business week family circle and esquire in an 
internship program sponsored by the us government and the 
magazines 
the interns seasoned journalists in their mid30s from 
