<TEXT>
chinas economy is sluggish verging on 
recession but exports are booming 
foreign investment has lagged since the brutal crackdown on 
dissent more than a year ago businessmen still worry about 
political instability and are put off by numerous roadblocks to 
profitable joint ventures 
trade is the bright spot in the chinese economy a western 
diplomat said on condition of anonymity if the current trend 
keeps up this years may be the biggest trade surplus in chinas 
history 
total trade rose 86 percent in 1989 to 1115 billion from 
january through june this year the 2565 billion in exports 
exceeded imports by 256 billion economists predict a 10 billion 
surplus for 1990 nearly double the record 1982 surplus of 563 
billion 
more industries produce goods for export because economic 
problems have shrunk domestic markets economists say china also is 
pushing exports in order to repay foreign loans many of which are 
due in 1992 
led by its freewheeling southern coastal provinces china is 
exporting more to the united states than ever before despite 
international censure of the harsh action against prodemocracy 
demonstrators in june 1989 
exports to the united states rose 43 percent last year to 1199 
billion according to us commerce department figures president 
bushs decision in may of this year to continue mostfavorednation 
status eliminated a major threat to the growing trade 
japan has not cashed in on the boom even though it has moved 
faster than other industrialized nations to ease sanctions imposed 
on beijing after the army assault on tiananmen square 
chinas exports to japan fell 35 percent to 343 billion in 
the first half of 1990 and imports from japan plunged 399 percent 
to 322 billion total trade between the two fell 5 percent in 
1989 from the previous year 
japanese businessmen were discouraged by tiananmen said 
nobuo maruyama senior economist at the institute of developing 
economies in tokyo 
after more than a decade of investing in china and waiting he 
said the japanese are turning to other asian nations with cheap 
labor such as india indonesia and the philippines 
according to the western diplomat japanese businessmen arent 
terribly enthusiastic about china as a place to invest or to 
trade since exports have fallen due to import restrictions 
theyve become hardnosed about doing business here 
japanese investors express the same concerns about china as 
about the soviet union joint ventures can find little hard 
currency to buy imports and factories face shortages of electricity 
and raw materials despite recent orders that special help be given 
to foreignfinanced companies 
economic austerity measures china imposed in late 1988 to curb 
inflation caused the domestic market to shrink 
the pall cast by the military crackdown and fears of future 
instability further dampened foreign enthusiasm and investment in 
china fell 147 percent in 1989 to 185 billion according to 
chinese estimates 
late last year political and economic risk consultancy ltd of 
hong kong issued an evaluation for 1990 that pronounced china by 
far the riskiest for foreign investment of 10 asian nations 
including the coupprone philippines 
after pointing to corruption red tape and the potential for 
unrest it said 
only investors with a longterm view of profitmaking that 
takes into account huge potential short and mediumterm pitfalls 
should consider a large commitment of capital at this time 
investors willing to take the risk favor chinas southern and 
coastal provinces which have thousands of factories financed from 
nearby hong kong 
these areas have been incorporated into the world economy and 
technological and managerial innovation are seeping in the 
diplomat said 
five or six years ago guangdong had a bad problem with 
quality now its the preferred source for quality and ontime 
delivery even when wages are higher than in thailand 
japanese companies with a labor shortage at home increasingly 
use assembly plants along the chinese coast that require minimal 
investment and training said maruyama the tokyo economist 
smaller japanese firms making laborintensive lowcost items 
like tableware compact cameras pajamas and baby clothes are 
staying in business by producing in china he said longterm 
joint ventures are too risky they only want to use the labor 
power 
one investment bright spot comes from taiwan whose businessmen 
seek factory sites abroad because of rapidly rising costs and 
pollution concerns at home 
taiwanese invested an estimated 550 million in china last year 
replacing japan as the thirdranked foreign investor after hong 
kong and the united states 
beijing has established special investment zones with 
concessionary terms for taiwanese in fujian province across a 
narrow strait from the island and in guangdong 
</TEXT>
