<TEXT>
the european communitys executive body 
on tuesday endorsed a blueprint for forming tighter economic and 
monetary links that would include a usstyle central bank in 1993 
it also would lead to creation of a single currency to be used 
throughout the dozen nations of the trading bloc 
the plan was offered to guide the nations at a special 
conference opening in december to make any needed changes in their 
founding treaty of rome to forge an economic and monetary union 
henning christophersen the communitys top economics official 
told a news conference that there should be a short period of time 
between establishing the europeanwide system of central banks 
dubbed eurofed and moving to a single currency 
the commissions blueprint will be discussed by economics and 
finance ministers of the dozen nations at a meeting in early 
september in rome 
the first stage of a threepart plan to put an economic and 
monetary union in place began on july 1 with greater coordination 
of policies among the community governments 
under the proposed blueprint the second stage would open on 
jan 1 1993 when work would get under way on the independent 
central banking system 
no date has been proposed for the final stage and introduction 
of the single currency 
