<TEXT>
the chicago board of trade said tuesday it is 
keeping an eye on soybean oil futures purchases amid reports that a 
unit of grainprocessing giant archer daniels midland is trying to 
corner the market 
market cornering is considered an unfair trading practice in 
which one company controls so much of a commodity it can wield an 
enormous influence over the price to the disadvantage of other 
traders 
the actions by the chicago board of trade one of the worlds 
leading commodities exchanges involves adm investor services an 
arm of adm the action comes about a year after the exchange issued 
an emergency order to break up a similar suspected attempt by an 
italian firm 
the commodity futures trading commission the federal agency 
that regulates the futures industry also said it was monitoring 
the market closely 
at adm headquarters in decatur ill aides said the firm had no 
comment 
adm is believed to hold more than half of all contracts for july 
and august delivery of soybean oil the wall street journal 
reported tuesday 
board of trade spokesman michael oakes said a considerable 
amount of bean oil has been purchased by adm 
im sure its being handled by our business conduct committee 
that they are looking into it oakes said 
until it reaches a point where we feel its a threat we just 
watch and monitor he said 
the board of trade determined there was a similar threat in july 
1989 when it appeared that ferruzzi spa one of the worlds 
largest soybean processors was trying to corner the soybean market 
ferruzzi had acquired large positions in the soybean market and 
owned more than fourfifths of all soybeans available for immediate 
delivery exchange officials and regulators concluded 
to keep ferruzzi from gaining control over soybean prices the 
cftc ordered the firm to reduce its holdings by 20 million bushels 
the board of trade then issued an emergency order requiring the 
liquidation of large positions in its july soybean contract 
that touched off wild swings in bean prices and prompted sharp 
criticism by farm groups and traders who saw the value of their 
futures holdings plummet 
</TEXT>
