<DOCNO> AP900821-0243 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
a state panel this month will consider 
restricting overthecounter sales of robitussindm and other cough 
remedies because they apparently have found a niche among teenage 
drug abusers officials said tuesday 
in one case last winter police in the pennsylvania community of 
waynesboro discovered dozens of discarded cough medicine bottles at 
a park frequented by teens an officer in the town of williamsport 
said a local boy reportedly suffered kidney problems because of his 
longterm abuse of cough syrups 
the fact is they are using the substance to get high said 
gerald keenan a physicians assistant in waynesboro who has 
identified cases involving cough medicine abuse 
we could not believe at the time we saw this that the level of 
intoxication was caused by cough syrup we thought it was 
caused by alcohol or something else he said 
a group of pharmacists from southcentral pennsylvania has asked 
the state department of health to pull robitussin and other cough 
medicines containing dextromethorphan from store shelves placing 
it under the control of pharmacists 
if the request is approved medicines containing 
dextromethorphan the most effective cough treatment on the market 
could be purchased only by people 18 and older consumers would 
have to sign a form to buy the products and would be permitted to 
purchase only 4 ounces within 72 hours 
the department needs to address it in some manner said jack 
ogun administrative secretary of the state drug device and 
cosmetic board 
the change would take it off display which would be the 
biggest crunch as far as sales ogun said 
dextromethorphan the active ingredient in about 75 cough 
medicines including robitussin and vicks 44 first came on the 
market as a prescription medicine in the mid1950s it was approved 
for overthecounter sales in 1976 
officials said the drug is safe and effective when taken as 
prescribed but it can produce effects ranging from lightheadedness 
to hallucinations when ingested in large doses ogun said someone 
who drinks large amounts runs a risk of convulsions a allergic 
reaction or a slowdown in bodily functions he was unaware of any 
fatalities from abuse 
there is no comprehensive information on the extent of abuses 
but ogun said he was aware of at least 50 cases statewide 
were concerned with it here locally because its not illegal 
to buy it possess it or drink it said waynesboro police chief 
glenn phenicie 
its probably been a problem longer than we realize he 
added 
pennsylvania is not the first state to confront abuse linked to 
robitussin and other cough preparations in utah a group of 
parents led a successful campaign to have robitussin voluntarily 
placed behind pharmacy counters 
police said they favored the proposal to limit access to cough 
syrups but the nonprescription drug manufacturers association an 
industry group said such a move would create an inconvenience for 
legitimate consumers 
for the industry there is a lot at stake according to kline amp 
co a new jersey business consulting firm the 14 leading cough 
syrups containing dextromethorphan have a wholesale market of about 
625 million annually nationwide 
controlling sales would literally remove that convenient 
access to that medicine to the vast majority of people who use it 
safely and effectively said vincent clough an association 
spokesman 
the industry would not oppose voluntary controls clough said 
he added that the association was working with local officials in 
waynesboro and had provided pamphlets for distribution 
ah robins which manufacturers robitussin cough syrups said 
in a statement it was working with the association and other 
companies to address the misuse of dextromethorphan 
the us food and drug administration has formed a task force 
that is looking into reported abuses of dextromethorphan 
the state board on drugs devices and cosmetics plans to hold a 
hearing on aug 28 on the pharmacists request a recommendation 
will be forwarded to the state secretary of health who has the 
authority to reclassify drugs 
</TEXT>
